The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Wednesday, March 10, 2004 				 HDFC Bank banks on rural accounts
 A STAFF REPORTER																								Calcutta, March 9: Sniffing opportunities, HDFC Bank is planning to focus on the small business segment and has identified semi-urban and rural areas to expand its network. 																								Outlining the banks future plans here today, managing director Aditya Puri said, Earlier, setting up branches in semi-urban areas was a requirement. But now its a business opportunity.																								If you want to become a large bank, you have to do rural business, Puri said.																								The small business segment where HDFC Bank wants to lend more includes traditional sweet makers, sari dealers and weavers for whom the bank will not only provide working capital but also its complete product range.																								At present, the bank is heavily into two-wheeler and car financing, personal loans, and credit cards business. It has also introduced private banking for its clients whereby the bank provides independent investment advice at different levels. 																								Puri also outlined the banks plans to beef up operations in the eastern region with emphasis on infrastructure development and product related businesses.																								We are entering a new phase, he said and added, Business is good, our product range is now complete and we are offering world class services. 																								At present, HDFC Bank has 286 branches in 150 locations across the country, with 25 branches in 12 cities across five states in this region.
